data.message: You guys told us at the beginning of this study you wanted to quit within the next 30 days. I was wondering if anyone of you may be ready to set a quit date or if you already have one? (Experts agree this is the most effective way to quit for good) #TDII
I quit real cigarettes on Monday the 21st. I'm less concerned about quitting my vape too, but still plan to do so before I graduate December 13th.

Great job 10406! How did the vape help you to quit? You know that since a lot of the long term consequences of vaping are still unknown I can't recommend them 100%, but I think it's great that you have quit smoking cigarettes - you can be proud of yourself!

Thanks! The vape helps because it's just a much easier transition than the gum or patch. It helps with the nicotine fix as well as things like throat hit and hand and oral fixation. It's easy to grab that when I'm having a craving and can actually feel satisfied. Now I'm gradually reducing the nicotine content of my liquid and how often I use it. It's much easier to ignore cravings when all I have is the vape, too.

Sounds like the vape is really working out for you 10406! That's great! I also think it's a very good idea to taper down your nicotine content if your aim is to become completely nicotine free in the long run and it sounds like you are well on your way to doing just that. I would advise you to try to not use your vape in the same situations you used to smoke cigarettes to also get rid of the psychological addiction (e.g., the connection of smoking with a certain mood or situation). What do you think about that?
I think that would really help! No more vape while driving.
What kind of alternatives do you have while driving? Singing along to your favorite tunes? Chewing gum or a toothpick? Or something else altogether? What do you think would work for YOU?
I like gum, coffee, and interesting radio like This American Life or NPR so I have something to really keep my attention off of it.

All of these sound like really good ideas 10406! Why don't you give them a try and let me know how it went next week? I am really impressed by your progress and your motivation :) Keep up the good work!
Also, don't forget to reward yourself for a job well done 10406! See you next week!

data.message: Hi guys, I am getting ready to start with session 3 on the wall of this event. Stop by if you want to learn about social support and quitting.
Hi guys – I have posted the content of today’s session here in the event. Feel free to check it out! See you next week.
Have you ever noticed a connection between smoking and your mood? Is there an emotional state that gets you to light up more frequently? #TDII

Ohhhh yes. I smoke much much more when I'm stressed or anxious. I'm also more likely to smoke when angry or depressed, but just a little bit less so than stressed. When I'm happy, I usually only smoke socially or when I'm driving.
Thanks for sharing 10406 - sounds like the negative emotions are your main triggers. Have you ever tried alternatives to smoking to improve your mood in these situations? How did it go?

I have, and some things help and some things don't. Typically, when things get too hectic I feel like I just don't have the willpower or mental energy to deal with whatever is going on /and/ fighting cravings. It's too easy to just say "screw it" and light up a cigarette without a second thought. I'm trying to be more concious about my mood when I get cravings now though. I've been trying to make myself wait at least 10-15 minutes before smoking when I know it's just because I'm upset. About half the time, the craving will pass.

That's a great strategy 10406! Most cravings actually go away within 5 minutes. If you want to can also try to keep track of your mood, pleasant activities, and smoking in this log that we have developed. It may help you to get a better understanding of your triggers. Do you think you will give it a try?
I will! I think for me though, I might tweak it a bit and mark my mood per cigarette as well as end of day.
I think just the added detail might help me personally.
Sure that's a great idea 10406! How motivated are you to quit smoking from 1 (least) to 10 (most)?

I would say about a 7 or 8 right now. Long term (within maybe 2-3 years), it's an unwavering 10. My husband and I want to start a family in 3-4 years and it is imperative that I've completely quit before then. I refuse to expose my hypothetical future kids to the risks associated with smoking while pregnant or second hand smoke. My main motivation short term is that the longer I keep smoking, the harder it will be to quit in the future.

These are important reasons 10406! I encourage you to make use of the resources here at TSP and to set a quit date when you are ready. Deciding on a quit date can help a lot an increases your chances!
I have to run for today - feel free to check out the next smoking cessation advice session tomorrow!

24.  Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or NRT’s (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. What are your thoughts on e-cigs? Have/would you ever try one? #ecig
The e cigs flavors are interesting
I have tried them and they have helped me cut down. Obviously did not help my nicotine addiction because it was easier to use..so I was using it any and everywhere. I do like them though.
I use mine every day it helps me quit one less cig at a time. I also love the flavor choices there are.. fda approved or not it helps me

I like the flavors and how they're not as harsh on my lungs as regular cigarettes. Of course like anything they have side effects and stuff, but everything does, you've just got to pick your bad habits I guess.

Mine has helped me cut down drastically. I still slip up sometimes, but I can go several days without lighting up a real cigarette. It helps with nicotine cravings, oral fixation, and (depending on voltage setting when I feel like it) even a little bit of that throat hit feeling. Right now I need a minimum 18mg liquid, but my goal is to 100% ween off of real cigarettes and then start gradually reducing the nicotine level of the liquid I use.
I heart my e-cig
They're helped me cut down a lot. I started with the nicotine set to high and gradually stated reducing it. I don't even smoke cigarettes anymore.

I feel as if the patch would help me the best
I think the gum or lozenge would help the most (depending on taste) because it would help with nicotine cravings as well as oral fixation.
I think the counseling and medication would work for me considering what my triggers are.
Probably the patch since I'm not as dependent on nicotine now. Also having my boyfriend around for support doesn't hurt. I've been slowly trying to come off cigarettes. Down to 3 a day. :)
I agree with 10411, bupropion is the best option for me since I'm on it anyways and it helps.
22.  What have you heard about bupropion to help people stop smoking? Would you consider taking a medication to help you quit? #beingconscious http://smokefree.gov/mg-bupropion.aspx
That's what I take to help with depression and also help me quit smoking. It works wonders, and also helps me not gain weight while I'm quitting as well.
I haven't heard anything about it. I'd be willing to try a medication. I'd like to see what the differences are between this one and the medicine from yesterday's post.
Yeah, what is the difference? I've never heard about it before.
I am willing to try considering it's with a perception and the fact that it helps with weight gain like 10441 says... Sign me up.!!!! Lol

Also just a side note: bupropion is the generic for Wellbutrin, which is a medicine for major depression and although it doesn't cause weight gain it can lower your seizure threshold, so if you've had seizures or are at risk for them it might not be the best idea. :)

Yes, they are more appealing because they don't smell awful, you can usually use them indoors, and you don't need to find somewhere to throw the ashes or filter or constantly carry (and subsequently lose) lighters. They seems safer to try since even though they have chemicals, the have /less/ chemicals. Plus, it's easy to think they're safer since (supposedly) the only ingredients other than nicotine (at least in vape juice) are food safe, and we don't yet have enough hard evidence to show a causal link to quite as many adverse effects of cigarettes caused by ingredients other than just the nicotine.

5.  Big tobacco companies aim to make their brand appealing. Become more conscious and learn to critique cigarette ads. In the ads below, how is Camel trying to manipulate its customers? #beingconscious
Sex appeal. Smoking isn't sexy though. It's gross.
Definitely sex appeal. Making smoking seem like it's an extremely relaxing and pleasurable act.
Looks nasty n tasteless
It's cool to smoke
Pretty obviously sex appeal. You know, with the prominent use of the word "pleasure" and ideal standards of attractiveness and whatnot.
Sexual attraction.
4.  Take this test to see how addicted to nicotine you are. What’s your reaction to your score? Are you surprised? #beingconscious http://www.nova.edu/gsc/nicotine_risk.html
I got no dependency. I'm not really surprised. I just do it to have something to do.

I got a zero. I'm a little surprised, but I think this test is just a little skewed to mornings. I have slow mornings and smoke more in the evening. According to this test, I'm less dependent because I smoke less during a certain time of day but I don't know if that's really a good measure of dependency.
I got a 4, I thought it would be higher
I got a 7. I honestly thought it would be lower.

I ended up with 3. Thought it would be higher..So sort of surprised. I think there are more factors involved in deciding dependency though. Considering someone who smokes Newports is ingesting more nicotine per cigarette..compared to someone who smokes Pall Malls.

I got 5. It really is grading on morning smokers. I mean the one question what cig would you hate to give up the most, morning cigarette, all others. Great choices. Wheres the dessert smoke after meals that's what'd i'd miss the most.

Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions!Since you told us at the beginning you are ready to quit smoking, I was wondering if anyone of you may be ready to set a quit date already? (Experts agree this is the most effective way to quit for good). #TDII
I haven't yet, maybe I should
Hi 10423, I would certainly recommend it. It can really help to have a day to focus on and to prepare for. When do you think you will be ready?
I set a quit day for August 26th

Great 10411! This is already one of the most important steps to quit smoking. Other things you may want to consider: 2. Get support from family/friends/colleagues. 3. Learn new skills and alternative behaviors for your high risk situations. 4. Depending on how much you smoke, I would definitely recommend that you consider trying some form of nicotine replacement therapy – we know that using these can dramatically decrease your cravings and withdrawal and increase your chances to quit for good. 5. Be prepared for relapse or difficult situations (e.g., alcohol, being around other smokers, stress, etc.). I know this sounds like a lot, but we will cover each of these aspects more in depth over the next weeks. How does this sound? Anything there you think may be useful?
I'm getting a lot of support from the one person who means the absolute world too me. He's basically mr only support. A lot of my friends smoke so I know it's going to be a difficult process.
I want to be ready now but withdraws were terrible. I might try the patch again. Friends make it difficult.
10411, it's great that you have a good friend to support you. We will certainly talk about strategies to approach risky situations over the next weeks in preparation of your quit day.
I know it can be difficult, but a good preparation will increase your chances of making it work!
10423, if withdrawal symptoms have been a problem for you in the past, I would definitely suggest some form of nicotine replacement like the patch or the gum.
What is your opinion on the use of a vaporizer as a cessation aid?

Great question 10406! The problem with e-cigs or vapes is that there is no clear data up to now showing that they really help smokers quit. Also, they are not regulated by the FDA, which means that it is unclear what is in them. For all we know, they may still be harmful to your health. I would recommend using nicotine replacement therapy: gum, patch, inhaler (prescription), or lozenge (prescription). Also, other prescription medication like zyban or chantix can be effective, but you have to talk to your doctor first to get a prescription. I recommend trying one of these options before trying an e-cig. Check this for additional information http://smokefree.gov/e-cigarettes.
Sorry guys I have to run. See you next week!
3.  Have any of you used a quit program or counseling program before? There are lots of free programs out there- how could they benefit you? What would make them better? #beingconscious
I've never used a program before. They could obviously benefit me by constructing to my quitting however since I've never used one I can't have an opinion on how they could be better.
The only thing I have ever done to quit is the patch. It made me sick, I'm not sure how programs could benefit me

I've never used a cessation program before. Sometimes I just don't feel like I have the time to deal with something like that. I might be more likely to utilize a program if it was an app of some sort or other type of remote program with a minimal time commitment, but I've just never looked into any.
I live in a small town, I don't believe any of these programs are close enough for me to actually put the effort into going not that i've looked into them.
We don't have groups and such around here. I live in the middle of nowhere. I am on medicine to help me quit smoking, though.

2.  What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation *If everyone posts a 10, text should say: Why is quitting smoking important to you? Is there anything that would make it even more important?
I work at a place where everyone smokes on break. Theres nothing better to do. Maybe a new job would make it easier, but I love my job.

I have severe anxiety problems and feel like smoking helps sometimes. I feel like it might be easier for me to quit once I get better insurance and can seek help for anxiety. I also smoke more around my mom cause when she wants to go outside for a cigarette I'll usually join her. It might be easier if she quit too.

Stress and depression. My boyfriend makes it even more important because he can't be around the smoke without his body freaking out. He doesnt want my health situation to get any worse than it already is and I don't want his to get bad because of me.
All of friends smoke. What motivates me is being healthy so I can have a baby and it be as healthy as possible.
My friends, my girlfriend, and my mother all smoke i'm entangled in a life of smoking but i'm sick of wasting money on tobacco and losing my breath so easily doing light cardio workouts.

data.message: Hi guys, I am getting ready to start with session 3 on the wall of this event. Stop by if you want to learn about social support and quitting.
Hi guys – I have posted the content of today’s session here in the event. Feel free to check it out! See you next week.

That’s it for today’s session.Between now and next time, practice being assertive. You can do it!Also, keep commenting on your Daily Tracking of Smoking, Mood, and Activities. Use this Pleasant Activities checklist to identify some activities that interest you. See you next time! Bye.

Sometimes you may have to respond by revealing to others how their behavior/comments make you feel. There are 3 steps to being successful with this: 1. Be neutral when describing their behavior to them2. Use “I feel” statements to describe how you feel about their comments/behavior3. Let them know what you want from them (i.e. a specific behavior change) that can help you as you quitHow do you think you could use these 3 steps in your situations to respond assertively?

Although other people may not always change their behavior upon your request, using these steps gives you a better chance of getting what you want and will leave you feeling better about yourself and your ability to be assertive.
Everyone is not the same personality. There are many personal styles of communicating:First is the passive style. Here’s a list:
Next there’s the aggressive style:
There’s one last personality type—the ASSERTIVE type:

By being assertive, you have the best chance of getting what you want and you will feel better about yourself by stating/responding that way.BUT…being assertive does not mean that you always have to speak your mind in every situation.

How would you handle the following situations without smoking?2. You just got out of school. A bunch of your friends are hanging out on the side of the school.You watch as someone in the group pulls out a pack of your favorite cigarettes and lights up.You smell the smoke and think about how you always used to enjoy a cigarette after school.Your friend notices that you’re looking at the cigarette, holds out the pack says, “Want one?”What would you do or say?

How would you handle the following situations without smoking?1. You’re at a party with a group of friends. Your friends are smoking.You’re feeling relaxed and thinking about how you always used to smoke at parties.Just as you start to say to yourself, “A cigarette would sure be good now,” your friend offers you a cigarette.What would you do or say?

Think positively about your decision to refuse a cigarette.It is easy to go along with what everyone else is doing.You are someone who makes a decision to do something and sticks to it!Respect yourself, and you will earn the respect of others in the long run.Here’s a pic you can use to remind you of the tips
Here’s another tip: Respond confidently.

One of the biggest challenges for an ex-smoker is declining a cigarette offer. Developing and practicing effective ways to turn down cigarette offers will reduce the chances of getting caught off guard.Anticipating these things is the first step to effectively turning down a cigarette offer. The next step is to respond effectively.
Welcome to the third session. How has it been for you this week? When was the last time you smoked?
People have been irritating me but the last time I smoked was three days ago.
Great job 10411 - so you pulled through despite difficult situations! How did you do it? What strategies did you use when you had urges?
I have a very short temper which hasn't been helping. Really the only thing stopping me is my friend shoes me pictures of what happens when you smoke.
Great - keep using this strategy if it works for now! I'm sure you'll also learn about other useful strategies during your participation in TSP!
How did you use your mood log this week?
